1.Introduction

The data that used in this homeworks is the hourly traffic volume for westbound I-94 highway in Minneapolis-St Paul, Minnesota between 2012-2018.It can be reached by the following link https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Metro+Interstate+Traffic+Volume.

2.Analysis Steps

Firstly needed packages is installed.The variable that will be predicted is traffic volume. As a first and simple observation, I checked acf for traffic volume. A height was noticed at the 24th lag as seen in figure 1, since it is an hourly data, which could be an hourly seasonalality sign. In order to easier the work with it I convert my data to data table. I add two other column which includes date and hour information. I have separated my data as test data and train data. The test data starts with year 2018.For the dates used in the data, there were also information such as temperature, weather description, weather main , whether there was a holiday or not.

3.Tasks

a)Task 1

First, I tried to set up simple linear models that explain traffic volume using temperature, date and hour.Then, I decided to use the weather description, weather and holidayi as a factor.According to this, the first model I set up explained the traffic volume by using hour,date and as factors weather description, weather main and holiday. The reason I included the hour information in this model was that the height of 24th lag in the acf function gave me an hourly seasonality sign, so I added the clock to my model, thinking that the same hour of each day contains a seasonality.The name of my first model is fit 3 and the summary of this model is seen in table 1 . Then I added the day, month, year columns to the train data with the information obtained from the date column.After that by taking the average I created daily data. I checked acf for the traffic volume of this daily data and observed a height in lag 7 as seen in figure 2, which was a daily sign of seasonality. Therefore, I added a column called weekday to the train data. In addition to the variables that I used in the fit 3 model, I added the weekday to my new model and called it fit 33.The summary of fit 33 can be seen in table 2. Then I created a new table called mtrend and transferred the hour, traffic_volume and datetime information on the train data to it.I added a column named index to the Mtrend table and built a model that explains traffic volume linearly with index. The summary of this model can be seen in table 3.Although R square lookspretty bad, it is possible to talk about an increasing trend due to intercept is positive. I also modeled the trend using the frollmean function with moving average. But when I plotted these two trends, the trend of the linear model seemed more appropriate.Therefore, I added the trend component I obtained from the linear model to the train data as column. Trend with linear approach can seen in figure 3 , trend with moving average approach can seen in figure 4. I have added 2 new columns to my Mtrend table.The first one is the result of subtraction of trend modelled by liner model from traffic volume. The second one,called detrendma, is the result of subtraction of trend modelled by moving average model from traffic volume.The reason I did this subtraction is to remove the influence of the trend when modeling seasonality. Then I decided to model seasonality using moving average methods.I used detrendma column for this purpose. As Acf lag 24 is high, I created a column called hour_effect considering that it was an hourly seasonality, and filled it with the average of the hours. Likewise, when I made the data daily, I saw a height in acf lag 7 so I created a column called weekday_effect and filled it with the average of the days. Afterwards, I thought that the holidays show seasonality because it is once a year and on the same date.I created a column called holiday_effect and filled it with the average of the holidays Finally, lag 168 was also high , which was a seasonal signal for certain hours of the certain days. So I created a column called dayhour_effect and filled it with the average of a certain hour of a certain weekday.

I thought these effects modeled seasonality and added the columns showing all these effects to the train data. Then, using the trend and seasonal effects, I created a model named lmson to explain the traffic volume.This model includes variables such as temp, weather_description and weather_main, as well as seasonal and trend related variables.Summary of this model can be seen in table 4 . The R square of this model looks pretty good, which may indicate that my model actually explains the train data relatively well.

I applied the same procedures I applied to the train data to the test data.

Finally, I have 3 different linear regression models. They are fit3, fit33 and lmson. Firstly, I tried to estimate the test data using these models, so I had an idea about the performance of the models.I plot these models which can be seen figure 5,figure 6 and figure 7 I created a prediction table and calculated mse mad and mape for each model as seen in table 5.Since fit3 has the smallest mape value it is the best model.

b)Task 2

I created a time series for the traffic volume in the train object. I made 24 as a frequency because lag 24 was high Acf. Then I created arima_model using the auto.arima function.Summary of this model seen in table 6.

I used arima with regressors as another model. I created a regressors matrix for this purpose. The variables I used as regressor were temparature, weekday and holiday effect. The name of this model is reg_arima.Summary of this model seen in table 7.

I made predictions for test data using by using these arima models.Plots of my predictions can seen in figure 8. Then I created a prediction table and calculated the mse, mad and mape values for both models.These values seen in table 8.Since regarima has a smaller mape value it is better than arima model.

c)Task 3

To be able to predict the next 24 hours with the linear model, the regressors of the next 24 hours had to be known. Since the hour effect was repeated every 24 hours, I used the hour effect in my test data. Likewise, the day effect was repeating every 7 days, the holiday effect was repeating every 365 days, and the dayhour effects were recurrent every 168 hours.So I was able to get these effects from my test data.I made a naive forecast for weather_main, weather_descriptiom, temperature and trend and used data from the previous day. I gathered all these regressors in a data table called sontable.I also added information such as hour, date, weekday for the next day in this table. Then, using the information in this table, I made predictions with my lmson, fit3 and fit33 models.Then I made another prediction with arima_model.I have created a matrix for regressors of the next 24 hours.By using these regressors I made my last predictions with reg_arima model. After all I had predictions that I made by using 5 different model.As I mentioned before the first three model was linear,the fourth one is arima and the last one was arima with regressors. Finally, I averaged my predictions using these five different models. I kept my forecasts in the my_forecasts variable.My forecasts can be seen in table 9.

# Modeling trend by using linear regression approach
mtrend = train[, list(date_time, traffic_volume, hour)]
mtrend[, `:=`(index, 1:.N)]  #creating an index
str(mtrend)
ltrend <- lm(traffic_volume ~ index, mtrend)  #modeling trend according to index
summary(ltrend)  #not a good r-squared but the positive intercept refers to increasing trend
ltrend_comp <- ltrend$fitted
mtrend[, `:=`(lr_trend, ltrend_comp)]
matplot(mtrend[, list(traffic_volume, lr_trend)], type = "l")

# Modeling trend by using moving average approach
window_size = 12
mtrend[, `:=`(ma_trend, frollmean(traffic_volume, (2 * window_size) + 
    1, align = "center"))]
matplot(mtrend[, list(traffic_volume, ma_trend)], type = "l")

matplot(mtrend[, list(traffic_volume, lr_trend, ma_trend)], type = "l")  #linear modeling trend has a better visualization as trend


train[, `:=`(trend, mtrend[, lr_trend])]  # adding trend component to trend data 

mtrend[, `:=`(detrendl, traffic_volume - lr_trend)]  #removing trend because it can affects seasonality
mtrend[, `:=`(detrendma, traffic_volume - ma_trend)]

# modeling seasonlity by using moving average approach
mtrend[, `:=`(mahour_effect, mean(detrendma, na.rm = TRUE)), 
    by = list(hour)]  #creating hour effect
plot(mtrend$mahour_effect[1:120], type = "l")
mtrend[, `:=`(weekday, train$weekday)]
mtrend[, `:=`(day_effect, mean(detrendma, na.rm = TRUE)), by = list(weekday)]  #creating day effect
plot(mtrend$day_effect[1:200], type = "l")
mtrend[, `:=`(indexses, (index%%168))]
mtrend[, `:=`(dayhour_effect, mean(detrendma, na.rm = TRUE)), 
    by = list(indexses)]  #creating day time effect
plot(mtrend$dayhour_effect[1:120], type = "l")
mtrend[, `:=`(holiday, train$holiday)]  #creating holiday effect 
mtrend[, `:=`(holiday_effect, mean(detrendma, na.rm = TRUE)), 
    by = list(holiday)]
plot(mtrend$dayhour_effect[1:120], type = "l")

train[, `:=`(hour_effect, mtrend$mahour_effect)]  #Adding all seasonality related variables to train data 
train[, `:=`(day_effect, mtrend$day_effect)]
train[, `:=`(dayhour_effect, mtrend$dayhour_effect)]
train[, `:=`(holiday_effect, mtrend$holiday_effect)]
# the third lm model

    hour_effect + day_effect + dayhour_effect + holiday_effect +
